Final Report- Songru Wang

Background:

The California Teachers Study (CTS) with a focus on OSHPD hospitalization records will serve as the dataset for the practicum. The CTS has OSHPD hospitalization data from three admission sources: Hospitalization (Patient discharge), ambulatory Surgery, and Emergency Department. In this project, only data from 2000 to 2015 will be used.

Introduction:

The primary analysis objective of this project is to: 1. Determine whether patients will die in certain time window 2. Whether certain patients traits (diet, physical activities, or smoking & alcohol use) will lead to higher possiblity of death

Method:

First, I combined the hospitalization data with the survey data based on participants key. Then I found there are multiple duplicate participant_key values for each participants. Since only the most recent data is most likely related to patients death, I only keep participant_key values with the most recent admission_dt to the hospital.

Second, I created several variables related to the date of death. In order to predict patients death during certain time periods, I created a variable about whether patients die in 2 months, a year, two years, or more than two years. Also, I created an variable showing the age of patients when they got admitted in the hospital.

Third, I started to clean data. After searching google, I deceided to transform each cause_death to their matching ICD 10 categories for better interpretation of the result. After searching the differences between codes of ICD9 and ICD10, I found codes of ICD 9 are mainly consisted of numbers, and the ICD 10 are mainly consisted of characters as its first character. Thus I checked the first 10 rows of diag_icd1; I found most of them are constructed by numbers. Thus, from diag_icd1 to diag_icd5, they are all ICD9 code. Therefore, Im going to transform these numerical variables to its categorical names. Then I check which variables have more than 70% missing values, and I deleted those variables. However, in the table, some categorical variables should not be deleted, such as endoca_self_q1,cervca_self_q1,ovryca_self_q1,lungca_self_q1,leuk_self_q1,hodg_self_q1,colnca_self_q1,thyrca_self_q1,meln_self_q1,diab_self_q1,stroke_self_q1,hrtatk_self_q1,hbp_self_q1. Since these variables only have one inpute value A, which means Yes, then missing values in these variables are possibly meant to be No.Thus, Im going to change NA values to B. Also, I deleted some variables that I think are not related to time_period and deceased. Later I impute categorical variables with mode and numerical variables with median.

Read Files

Fourth, I did exploratory data analysis. I want to find which category of trigger_of_death is more. In the graph, I found most patients die from dieaseas of circulatory systems Then I plot the major_diag_cat_cde. I found for more admitted patients, they were diagnozed with Musculoskeletal System & Connective Tissue, Diseases & Disorders.

Finally, I build 4 random forest models on four situations. The first is to predict which physical activity, diet, smoking& drinking history variables is most influential to outcome variable deceased. The rest of the three models are to predict patients with which variables are more likely to die within two years, two years, and more than two years. For better interpretation and analysis, all these models only include variables related to physical activity, diet, and smoking& drinking history. After having the variable importance, I will pick several important variables to do exploratory data analysis. To check the relationship between that variable and the outcome variable.

First Model:

Among all these variables, top 3 most important variables are smoke_lifeexpo, allex_life_hrs, stand_hrs. In conclusion, A. Most smokers have 50 years of exposure to smoke. And smoking taboco is positively related to death B. allex_life_hrs is Strenuous + moderate exercise hrs/wk over year past 3 yrs. According to the graph, it showed that the possiblity of dying between not exercising and exercising is not much different. C. According to the graph, patients who has moderate standing hrs (from 1-9 hrs per day) is less likely to die; however, patients who not stand or stand more than 10 hours per day are more likely to die.

AUC for training set is 0.7795; AUC for testing set is 0.7841. This indicate that: 1) the model is not overfiting or underfitting; 2) the model performs well in predicting patients death

2-4 th models

For rest of the three models, allex_life_hrs, diet_plant, diet_saladwine are three most important variables. And there relationship to the time period variable is: A. Patients with exercises of more than 20 hrs per week over a year have higher possiblity of dying B. Patients with diet plant score equal to or more than 6 have higher possibility of not dying C. When patients have diet_saladwine score -4 or 6, they will have the highest possiblity (40%) of not dying

Last Model

In these models, I included all variables except trigger_of_death and discharge_death. Decease is used as the outcome variable. Then I found that in three time window variables, twoMonths is more important to the outcome variable deceased. Thus, I can say patients in these datasets are more likely to die in two months. And the auc of training and testing set are 0.9605 and 0.9508.

## Conclusion In conclusion, patients are more likely to die in two months after their discharge date at the hospital. And patients with Musculoskeletal System & Connective Tissue, Diseases & Disorders and dieaseas of circulatory systems have more populations in dying. Also, A. patients who not stand or stand more than 10 hours per day are more likely to die. B. Smoking is linked to higher death rate C. Patients with diet plant score equal to or more than 6 have higher possibility of not dying D. When patients have diet_saladwine score -4 or 6, they will have the highest possiblity (40%) of not dying

Since the dataset is not large enough and there are too many duplicate values, the result and prediction is not representative enough. Thus, larger dataset is required for better prediction.
